Source: American College Health Association Online
<http://www.acha.org/news/resp_illness4_2_01.htm>

Investigation of Respiratory Illness Among College "Spring Break" Visitors
to Acapulco, Mexico
----------------------------------------------------------
Update: 2 April 2001
The Pennsylvania Department of Health and the Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention are beginning an investigation of clusters of acute
respiratory illness among students who traveled to Acapulco, Mexico for
"Spring Break" in early March [2001]. Based on clinical findings and chest
radiographs, we suspect a fungal infection such as histoplasmosis or
coccidioidomycosis. Laboratory confirmation is pending.
At this time, we are aware of illness in student travelers from 2
Pennsylvania colleges in different areas of our state. Both groups stayed
at the same hotel in Acapulco, Mexico during approximately the first week
of March. (Of note, the hotel is said to have had "major construction" at
the time of their visit. Also, there is a report of an earthquake in the
region at the time of the trips. The significance of the earthquake to this
investigation is not yet clear.) We have also heard rumors of illness among
students from a different campus in another state but this has not yet been
confirmed.
The total number of ill college students in Pennsylvania is not clear, but
at this time as many as 16 from one campus and 11 from another campus have
been reported to have suffered some fever and/or respiratory symptoms. The
students' illnesses mostly began during the last week of March [2001] and
generally include fever, dry cough, and substernal non-pleuritic chest
pain, with chest radiographs showing infiltrates consistent with a fungal
infection. Students initially treated with antibacterials such as
azithromycin showed no improvement, and some are now on oral antifungal
therapy (it is too early to tell if they are improving). Several were
briefly hospitalized but none are life-threateningly ill; others had less
severe symptoms and were treated on an outpatient basis.
If you become aware of other ill visitors to Acapulco, please let your
local or state public health authorities know, and we would appreciate it
if you would also let us know at the numbers below.
Thank you,
Andre Weltman, M.D., M.Sc.
Public Health Physician
Division of Communicable Disease Epidemiology
Pennsylvania Department of Health
tel: (717) 787-3350
fax: (717) 772-6975
<aweltman@state.pa.us>
