[2]
Source: American College Health Association Online
<http://www.acha.org/news/resp_illness4_5_01.htm>
Investigation of Respiratory Illness Among College "Spring Break" Visitors
to Acapulco, Mexico
----------------------------------------------------------
Update 5 April 2001
Suspect cases are now being reported from multiple states, involving
similar symptoms with varying degrees of morbidity. The investigation by
CDC and now several state and local health departments continues. Please
contact your local or state health department to report ill travelers to
Acapulco. They will soon be able to work with you to complete a
standardized report form so that we collect the same information from all
the involved persons across the country.
At least one press report has appeared which incorrectly asserts that
histoplasmosis has been established as the cause of this outbreak
(Philadelphia Inquirer, 5 Apr 2001). _Histoplasma [capsulatum_] is
certainly on the list of possible etiologies, but at this time we do NOT
know what the actual etiology is in any patient. Other possibilities to
consider include other fungi such as _Coccidioides [immitis_], and various
other "atypical" causes of pneumonia such as _Legionella_, _Mycoplasma_, or
Adenovirus. In at least one cluster of ill college travelers, tests for
_Legionella_ antibodies and urine antigen were negative [Serum antibody to
_Legionella pneumophila_ detects antibodies to _L. pneumophila_ serogroups
1-4. This test will not detect infection with other _Legionella_ species
and may be negative during the acute infection. A convalescent sample
should be sent 2 to 3 weeks after the initial specimen to look for a rise
in titer. The _Legionella_ urinary antigen test is a rapid assay for the
detection of _Legionella pneumophila_ serogroup 1 antigen in urine samples.
The test is particularly useful in the early stages of disease allowing for
the diagnosis during the acute phase. This test will not detect infection
with _L. pneumophila_ serogroups other than 1 or with other _Legionella_
species. - Man. Ed. DS]. In some instances, symptoms have lingered despite
therapy with azithromycin or quinolone antimicrobials. There is also a
report of a patient who did not improve after therapy with an oral
antifungal agent.
We are particularly interested in hearing about negative and positive
diagnostic tests, including especially from the more severely ill or
hospitalized patients. CDC will be coordinating outbreak laboratory studies
with your state health department. Please contact your health department if
you can provide serum, nasopharyngeal swabs, or tissue samples (such as
from transbronchial biopsy) from ill travelers.
Thank you,
Andre Weltman, M.D., M.Sc.
Public Health Physician
Division of Communicable Disease Epidemiology
Pennsylvania Department of Health
tel: (717) 787-3350
fax: (717) 772-6975
<aweltman@state.pa.us>
